hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider an abelian group $G$ of order 100. A key property of this group is that there exists an element $g \in G$ whose order is exactly 100.

According to the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups, any such group $G$ can be expressed as a direct product of cyclic groups in the form $\mathbb{Z}_{n_1} \times \mathbb{Z}_{n_2} \times \dots \times \mathbb{Z}_{n_k}$, where the integers $n_i$ are called the invariant factors of $G$ and they must satisfy the divisibility condition $n_1 | n_2 | \dots | n_k$.

What is the set of invariant factors for the group $G$?

A. {100}

B. {2, 50}

C. {5, 20}

D. {10, 10}

E. {4, 25}
